{
  "texts": [
    "Given a vector z ∈ R n, its transpose is denoted as z ⊤ and its i-th element as z i.",
    "A vector of n ones is denoted by 1 n. For a vector z ∈ R n observed over m time steps, i.e., z(1),..., z(m), where the set of time indices is I = {1,..., m} with cardinality |I|, the matrix containing these m observations is denoted in bold as z = z(1)... z(m) ∈ R n×m and can be compactly expressed as z = z(k) k∈I.",
    "Matrices containing different vectors observed over m time steps included in I, e.g., z 1, z 2, are generically indicated using calligraphic letters, i.e.,D = z ⊤ 1 z ⊤ 2 ⊤.In this paper, we make use of the Mahalanobis distance [21], a statistical process control metric used to quantify how far two datasets are from each other in terms of mean and covariance.Definition 2.1: (Mahalanobis distance).",
    "Consider a benchmark dataset z = z(k) k∈I containing |I| observations of a variable z ∈ R nz, and a monitoring dataset z = z(k) k∈ I with | I| observations of z ∈ R nz, where I and I contain the time indices of the observations in z and z, respectively.",
    "The statistical Mahalanobis distances T 2 of z with respect to z are defined asT 2 ( z, z) = z(k) -µ z ⊤ (Σ z) -1 z(k) -µ z ⊤ k∈ I,(1)whereµ z = 1 |I| k∈I z(k),(2)Σ z = 1 |I| -1 k∈I z(k) -µ z z(k) -µ z ⊤."
  ]
